<td id="title_text"><h1><a title="Fountain Concentrate" class="currentChild" href="Fountain_Concentrate">Fountain Concentrate</a></h1></td>



</tr></table>
</td>
</tr></table></div>



<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
Term for the undiluted substances comprising an offset press's <a title="Fountain Solution" href="Fountain_Solution">fountain solution</a>. Fountain concentrate commonly consists of alcohol or an alcohol substitute, a <a title="Wetting Agent" href="Wetting_Agent">wetting agent</a>, a <a title="Gum" href="Gum">gum</a>, a fungicide, and perhaps a <a title="Drying Stimulator" href="Drying_Stimulator">drying stimulator</a> and/or an <a title="Antifoaming Agent" href="Antifoaming_Agent">antifoaming agent</a>, with variations on the actual composition in order to be compatible with the chemistry of the ink and/or <a title="Substrate" href="Substrate">substrate</a> used. Fountain concentrate is often premixed by the supplier. Adding a recommended quantity of water produces the fountain solution itself. Typical dosages are quite low, usually between 2 and 3% fountain concentrate mixed into the water, although IPA-free dampening might require 4 or 5% dosage.  (See <a title="Fountain Solution" href="Fountain_Solution">Fountain Solution</a> and <a title="Dampening System" href="Dampening_System">Dampening System</a>.) Fountain concentrate is also called <a title="Fountain Etch" href="Fountain_Etch">fountain etch</a> and <a title="Etch" href="Etch">etch</a>. 
</p>
